tten (the sole survivor of a litter that had been drowned). “Go away, go away, later.” The little girl left. There was a long silence. After a while, slowly, silently, he began twisting her wrists—he longed to break all of her, to dislocate all her joints with loud cracks. She started to cry. Then he sat down at the table and pretended to read the newspaper. She went out into the garden, but soon returned. “I can’t keep it back any longer. I have to tell you everything.” And with an 